Frequently rhetorical point is given by alliteration, as in ‘magna fama . . . mala’ (c. 5, 4), ‘deposcendis . . . detrectandis' (c. 11, 4), ‘ paena . . . paenitentia' (c. 19, 3), ‘offendere . . . odisse’ (c. 22, 5), ‘vota virtusque,' ‘ victoribus . . . victis ’ (c. 33, 4 ; cp. c. 18, 7), ‘ mucrones ac manus' (c. 36, 1), ‘virtutibus . . . vitiis’ (c. 41, 4), ‘ famam fatumque' (c. 42, 4), ‘inglorios et ignobilis oblivio obruit' (c. 46, 6). Also the rhetorical structure of clauses known as chiasmus is seen here and there (e. 18, 73 20, 2; 25, 3; 28, 2; 36, 1), and some of the personifications, as those of ‘ ira ’ and ‘victoria' (c. 16, 1), ‘pugnae’ (c. 30, 3), ‘ gladii' (c. 36, 1), are unusually bold.

In these characteristics Tacitus is somewhat in contrast with his after self, as also in the less prominence of many of his favourite modes of compression.
